{{Expand German|Deutsche Afrika-Schau|date=March 2018}}

'''Deutsche Afrika-Schau''' ("German Africa Show") was an exhibition touted as an ethnographic depiction of African people and customs that toured Germany in the 1937 to 1940.<ref>https://blackcentraleurope.com/sources/1914-1945/the-german-africa-show-die-deutsche-afrika-schau-ca-1936/</ref> It was a continuation of earlier Völkerschauen ("people shows"), a [[human zoo]] anthropological exhibition that toured in Germany in the decades before Nazi Germany. Nazi propaganda used the Deutsche Afrika-Schau to promote ideology supporting German colonization in Africa and featured depictions of loyal African [[Askari]] soldiers at a time when African minorities in Germany were denied basic rights. [[Bayume Mohamed Husen]] who had taught [[Swahili language|Swahili]] was part of the show along with  [[Kwassi Bruce]] and Adolf [[Hillerkus]]. Germans with African ancestry dressed up in costumes and performed dances and other acts for the show.

