[[File:King Goodwill Zwelithini.jpg|thumb|[[Goodwill Zwelithini kaBhekuzulu]] revived the festival in 1990.]] [[File:Courge encore verte.jpg|thumb|The dashing of a [[calabash]] by the [[List of Zulu kings|Zulu King]] signifies that the people may now enjoy the fruits of the harvest.]] '''Umkhosi Wokweshwama''' {{IPA-zu|um̩kʰoːsi woɠʷeʃʷaːma|}} ("[[first fruits]] festival"), recently also known as '''Umkhosi Woselwa''' {{IPA-zu|um̩kʰoːsi woseːlʷa|}} ("[[calabash]] festival"), is the annual [[harvest festival]] of the [[Zulu people]], observed around the [[December solstice]]. It takes place at the Enyokeni Royal Palace in [[Nongoma]], KwaZulu-Natal, and is presided over by the [[List of Zulu kings|Zulu King]], who conducts a [[tasting]] ceremony as [[sacred king]], closed by the dashing of a [[calabash]] to signify that the people may now enjoy the fruits of the harvest; this role was historically expanded by [[Shaka]] to have more military significance with a [[Muster (military)|muster]] and [[Military parade|parade]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GNpVU0fllzgC&pg=PA76|title=Healing Traditions: African Medicine, Cultural Exchange, and Competition in South Africa, 1820–1948|last=Flint|first=Karen Elizabeth|date=2008|publisher=Ohio University Press|year=|isbn=9780821418499|location=|pages=76|language=en|deadurl=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209210925/https://books.google.com/books?id=GNpVU0fllzgC&pg=PA76|archive-date=2018-02-09|df=}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Snedegar|first=Keith|date=1998|title=First Fruits Celebrations among the Nguni Peoples of Southern Africa: An Ethnoastronomical Interpretation|url=http://adsabs.harvard.edu/full/1998JHAS...29...31S|journal=Journal for the History of Astronomy, Archaeoastronomy Supplement|volume=29|pages=31–38|via=Astrophysics Data System}}</ref><ref name=":0" /><ref name=":3">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PtakAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA33|title=Zulu Kings and their Armies|last=Canwell|first=Diane|date=2004-09-30|publisher=Pen and Sword|year=|isbn=9781844150601|location=|pages=33–36|language=en|deadurl=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209210925/https://books.google.com/books?id=PtakAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA33|archive-date=2018-02-09|df=}}</ref><ref name=":4" /> It was revived by the current king [[Goodwill Zwelithini kaBhekuzulu]] in 1990, after a ban by British colonial authorities following the 1879 [[Battle of Isandlwana]] and Zulu defeat in the [[Anglo-Zulu War]] (the last was held in winter 1877–78, though some claim continuity as a less elaborate event).<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wdrpAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA25|title=Religions of South Africa (Routledge Revivals)|last=Chidester|first=David|date=2014-06-27|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781317649878|location=|pages=25–27|language=en|deadurl=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209210925/https://books.google.com/books?id=wdrpAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA25|archive-date=2018-02-09|df=}}</ref><ref name=":3" /><ref name=":4">{{Cite web|url=http://www.saflii.org/za/cases/ZAKZPHC/2009/75.pdf|title=In the High Court Of South Africa KwaZulu-Natal-Natal, Pietermaritzburg – Case No: 10237/2009|last=|first=|date=2009-01-04|website=Southern African Legal Information Institute|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103011759/http://www.saflii.org/za/cases/ZAKZPHC/2009/75.pdf|archive-date=2018-01-03|dead-url=no|access-date=|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EXbBS63DMq0C&pg=PA59|title=Spearheading Debate: Culture Wars & Uneasy Truces|last=Dubin|first=Steven C.|date=2012|publisher=Jacana Media|year=|isbn=9781431407378|location=|pages=59|language=en|deadurl=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209210925/https://books.google.com/books?id=EXbBS63DMq0C&pg=PA59|archive-date=2018-02-09|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1538807/Bulls-killing-in-Zulu-rite-condemned-as-barbaric.html|title=Bulls' killing in Zulu rite condemned as barbaric|last=Bevan|first=Stephen|date=2007|access-date=2018-01-01|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235|deadurl=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102015901/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1538807/Bulls-killing-in-Zulu-rite-condemned-as-barbaric.html|archive-date=2018-01-02|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rautenbach|first=Christa|date=2011-12-19|title=Umkhosi Ukweshwama: Revival of a Zulu Festival in Celebration of the Universe’s Rites of Passage|url=https://papers.ssrn.com/abstract=1974444|location=Rochester, NY}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/02/17/magazine/the-chief-steps-forward.html|title=The Chief Steps Forward|last=Johannesburg|first=Christopher S. Wren; Christopher S. Wren is The Times's bureau chief in|date=1991-02-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-01-01|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|deadurl=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102072804/http://www.nytimes.com/1991/02/17/magazine/the-chief-steps-forward.html|archive-date=2018-01-02|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/02/17/magazine/the-chief-steps-forward.html|title=The Chief Steps Forward|last=Johannesburg|first=Christopher S. Wren; Christopher S. Wren is The Times's bureau chief in|date=1991-02-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-01-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|deadurl=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102072804/http://www.nytimes.com/1991/02/17/magazine/the-chief-steps-forward.html|archive-date=2018-01-02|df=}}</ref>
The festival has mass participation by young men, as [[Umkhosi woMhlanga]] has by young women. There is a [[sacred bull|black bull sacrifice]] in the king's [[kraal]] as the young men work together to kill the animal without weapons, which was the subject of a failed lawsuit by [[Animal welfare and rights in South Africa|South African animal rights activists]] in 2009.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/09/world/africa/09safrica.html|title=Spilling the Blood of Bulls to Preserve Zulu Tradition|last=Bearak|first=Barry|date=2009-12-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-31|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|deadurl=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101082445/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/09/world/africa/09safrica.html|archive-date=2018-01-01|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2009-12-04-bullkilling-can-go-ahead-says-court|title=Bull-killing can go ahead, says court|last=|first=|date=2009-04-12|work=Mail & Guardian|access-date=2018-01-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150516042703/http://mg.co.za/article/2009-12-04-bullkilling-can-go-ahead-says-court|archive-date=2015-05-16|dead-url=no|language=en|df=}}</ref><ref name=":4" /> The sacrifice of the bull is seen as transferring the bull's power to the king.<ref name=":2" /> The [[INkatha (Zulu artifact)|iNkatha]] was also renewed.<ref name=":3" /> The Scottish mythographer [[James George Frazer]] speculated that this reflected an ancient practice of sacrificing the king himself.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iaxQP9WoEXwC&pg=PA67|title=The Golden Bough|last=Frazer|first=James George|date=2012-04-26|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=|isbn=9781108047371|location=|pages=67–68|language=en|deadurl=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209210925/https://books.google.com/books?id=iaxQP9WoEXwC&pg=PA67|archive-date=2018-02-09|df=}}</ref>
The Kingdom of Swaziland's counterpart event is [[Incwala]], part of a larger family of [[Nguni people|Nguni]] [[First Fruits (Southern Africa)|First Fruit traditions]].<ref name=":1" /> Aspects of the festival have been adapted by the Zulu-initiated [[Nazareth Baptist Church]] in its celebration of [[Christmas]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f8sUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA112|title=The Theology of a South African Messiah: An Analysis of the Hymnal of The Church of the Nazarites|last=Oosthuizen|first=Gerhardus Cornelis|date=1967|publisher=Brill Archive|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=112|language=en|deadurl=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209210925/https://books.google.com/books?id=f8sUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA112|archive-date=2018-02-09|df=}}</ref> The Zulu festival was a partial inspiration for the modern African-American holiday of [[Kwanzaa]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QGCOAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA83|title=Kwanzaa: Black Power and the Making of the African-American Holiday Tradition|last=Mayes|first=Keith A.|date=2009-09-10|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781135284008|location=|pages=84|language=en|deadurl=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209210925/https://books.google.com/books?id=QGCOAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA83|archive-date=2018-02-09|df=}}</ref>
